places called Monforte, from Latin <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ (genitive <i>montis</i>) + <i>fortis</i> ‘strong’, probably a reference to the strategic position of these locations.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Montfort  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice De Montfort was born in 1050. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Gilbert De Gaunt. She died in 1091, in Folkingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41, and was buried in Bardney, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1050–1091":"1050–1091","1048–1095":"1048–1095","1080–1139":"1080–1139","1086–1174":"1086–1174","1080":"1080","1091":"1091","1139":"1139","1048":"1048","1174":"1174","1086":"1086","1095":"1095","1050":"1050","about 1086":"umbes 1086","Bardney, Lincolnshire, England":"Bardney, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Folkingham, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Folkingham, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","Folkingham, Lincolnshire, England":"Folkingham, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1050–1091":"1050–1091","1048–10